'''Amanohiwashi no Kami''' (天日鷲神) is a {{ill|deity|ja|神 (神道)|translation=god}} appearing in {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話}}. The deity appears in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}} and {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古語拾遺}}. The ancestor deity of the {{ill|Inbe clan|ja|忌部氏}} (inbe) of Awa, who developed the Awa region and initiated the spinning industry by planting hemp.
Also called '''Oegami''' ('''麻植神,''' おえのかみ) and '''Imbe no Kami''' ('''忌部神,''' いんべのかみ) <ref name="weekly_shrine"/>. Additionally, known as '''Amanohiwashikakeru Yano Mikoto''' ('''天日鷲翔矢命,''' あめのひわしかけるやのみこと), a descendant deity of {{ill|Takami Musubi|ja|タカミムスビ|1=Takamimusubi|translation=Takami no Mikoto}} or {{ill|Kamimusuhi|ja|カミムスビ|1=Kamimusubi|translation=Kamimusuhi no Mikoto}}.
== Overview == According to the mythology, when {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami}} entered the {{ill|Amanoiwato|ja|天岩戸|1=Amano-Iwato|lt=Heavenly Rock Cave}}, the gods began dancing in front of the rock door, and Amanohiwashi no Kami played a stringed instrument. When a hawk landed on the tip of the string, many gods took it as an auspicious sign to brighten the world, and the deity's name was augmented with the character for hawk, becoming Amanohiwashi no Mikoto. Later, {{ill|Hirata Atsutane|ja|平田篤胤}} mentioned that the hawk was the same bird that contributed to Emperor Jimmu's victory in battle <ref name="weekly_shrine">{{Cite book|和書|author=|title=週刊日本の神社 No67 忌部神社 大麻比古神社 |publisher=デアゴスティーニ・ジャパン|date=2015-5-28|page=14-19}}</ref>.
In the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}, it is written that in one account of the Amanoiwato, "Amanohiwashi no Mikoto of Awa's Imbe, the distant ancestor, made {{ill|hemp|ja|木綿 (ゆう)|translation=wooden strips}}."
According to the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古語拾遺}}, Amanohiwashi no Kami is one of the four deities who followed {{ill|Futodama|ja|フトダマ|translation=Futodama no Mikoto}}. Also, when {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami}} hid in the Amanoiwato, it is said that Amanohiwashi no Kami planted hemp and mulberry to make the offerings. Therefore, Amanohiwashi no Kami is also called "Moegami" (おえのかみ) and became the deity of the spinning and paper-making industries. Additionally, {{ill|Amanotomohime|ja|天富命|translation=Amanotomohime}} led the grandchildren of Amanohiwashi no Kami to Awa and planted hemp and {{ill|asa|ja|アサ|translation=hemp}}.
In the "Kokuzou Honki" section of the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀}}, it is said that in the era of Emperor Jimmu, Amanohiwashi no Mikoto was appointed as the Ise Kokuzou. Meanwhile, in the {{ill|Ise no Kuni Fudoki|ja|伊勢国風土記}}'s remaining passages, it is written that Emperor Jimmu sent Amanohiwashi no Mikoto to Ise, where he subdued Isetsuhiko.
Additionally, Amanohiwashi no Kami is generally known as {{ill|Otori-sama|ja|お酉様}} at {{ill|Ōtori Shrine|ja|大鷲神社|lt=Ōtori Shrines}}, and is worshipped as the guardian deity of bountiful fishing, commercial prosperity, good luck, pioneering, and industry.
Amanohiwashi no Kami is enshrined at {{ill|Inbe Shrine|ja|忌部神社}} and {{ill|Tori Shrine|ja|鷲神社}}. Imbe Shrine is associated with the Mikake family, who are believed to be descendants of the Awa Imbe and grow hemp for the emperor's enthronement ritual <ref name="weekly_shrine"/>.
According to the {{ill|Shinsen Shojiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku}}, Amanohiwashi no Kami is considered an ancestor of the Inukai clan and Amakoto no Muraji.
